I had no time to write an elaborate Thanksgiving post. Between being behind a hot stove and fully present laughing, toasting, movie quote roasting, in short sprinkling love all over my family like I’ve tried to do since they were old enough to remember, I’m reminded that that’s what it’s all about. Birthdays, Thanksgivings, Christmas’, that’s it. Not the things, the fancy table settings, or fine wines, you’ll forget all about them by the time the next holiday rolls around. What you don’t forget is the family bond, your Mom in her apron & spiked beer in her hand, the hugs & the music she turned up when that one song came on, the rosy glow on her cheeks from cooking whatever she’d just poured her whole heart into, and how somehow she’d still find the energy to make you feel like a royal guest in her humble home. I’m grateful that thanks to my Mother & Grandmother’s ways, I can continue carrying on w/their traditions. If for a day… putting on hold the 10 diff things that pull you in 10 diff directions most of the time. To make lasting memories, some captured, others existent only in your mind. It’s all worth it, every sacrifice. 

Thank you @merrickmortonphotos 📷 for sharing nostalgias through pictures and transporting us to another space and time. Missing my Mom so very much this year, I can only hope she’s sitting beside me, smiling back from the other side. 

Happy Thanksgiving & Happy Holidays from me and mine. ❤️🙏🏾

Sure, I’ll tell you what the 90’s in LA were like… I’ll tell you about the Newberry’s and Pete’s Burger’s on Hoover St. Or Hoover Park for your all-encompassing neighborly recreation. I’ll tell you about the Christmas layaway plans at K-Mart & Crystal Promotions… the USC Sunday BBQ’s thanks to your Dad’s lead in the Catering Dept. Sure I’ll tell you about the fine dining establishments such as Pollo Loco where a family of 4 would splurge on a $40 dinner once a week. Or the 1-bedroom apartments that facilitated family parties for 50 if the chairs in the hallway were positioned just right. Or the Slauson & Alameda Swapmeets, where your Mom came up on makeup & accessories & your Vans & Cortez were affordable.. enough. Or how when the budget was leaner than lean, Payless’ Pro Wings & wanna-be Keds kinda looked alright. Or Grandma’s RTD shopping runs to DTLA and El Piojito in MacArthur Park because your toiletries & Salvi home decor were BBB (bueno, bonito, barato). Oh I’ll tell you all about the man purses better known as Panasonic & Zenith pullout stereos and no parked cars without a club (and I’m not talking El Rey or El Parral). I remember vividly, the friends that would spot you for a Wendy’s cheeseburger and a mini-mini Frosty Freeze. The streaks you’d split in half and the black piecebooks you’d land a corner spot in. The story high hit-ups that wouldn’t let you second guess what side of the tracks you were on. The crash units that were as common in the neighborhood as your verdulero and paletero man. The pictures no one remembers taking, that would resurface in the form of a xerox thanks to that one disposable camera that one guy had. Or the social media posts and wide range of cultural references that didn’t exist because we didn’t have the internet at the time. 

Sure, I’ll tell you what the 90’s in LA were like… 

~D ❤️✌🏽

First half of 2022 recap 🎞️ 

1. Took my family up to Big Bear 
2. Honed the gift of creativity 
3. Started some home upgrades 
4. Got more in touch w/nature 
5. Brought home our beloved Lucy R.I.P. ❤️‍🩹
6. Brought out the shine for my Mom✨ 
7. Caught great performances w/friends
8. Took out of state pop-up opportunities 
9. Art collab’d w/my 15yr old son for the 1st time
10. Shot my first music video with Beyoncé

Crazy how going month by month through your camera roll puts so much perspective on things your mind starts filing away little by little. 💞🙏🏾

Second half of 2022 in brief 🎬 and so much in between. 🫶🏽

1. Paid homage to the late great Bob Roberts 
2. Ventured out with my kids 💕
3. Attended art shows & bonded w/titans 
4. Took cute lil walks on the beach w/my BFF 
5. Art collab’d w/Eliseo for DxC (another 1st)
6. Saw the goat perform w/the Big Steppers 
7. Fell in love… w/ a custom engraved DxC plaque 
8. Got a pretty black & grey rose tattooed 🌹
9. Shot in my truest form w/my fav Venician 
10. Went to NYC & all I got was this neatto sticker 

So much to say about closing this year & chapter. A lot of wins, a lot of losses. But all in all with good health, family tighter, and motivation to keep working hard & creating from a place of love. I’ll write some more, maybe tmrw maybe soon. For now… Happy New Year!🥂🎆💫 Love y’all so much! In ‘23 let us try not to be so hard on ourselves, to show up for own person as we do for others, and give ourselves grace any chance we get. Lastly, let us be hopeful but also reminded that we do not control destiny. If things work out differently than we picture, it’s probably for our own good.  Wishing you all the very best! 💜 Abrazos!*~

So much comes to my mind when I see this foto… mainly amazed at how things go full circle. Growing up in #LA as a teen running in tagger circles, I had my mentors, and #Defer was definitely one of them. I remember how much I looked up to these guys out there becoming giants in the scene I aspired to be a part of. Despite life taking me in a different direction to embrace motherhood, I’m proud to see how far graff artists like @deferk2s have come! Thank you Defer for paving a path, creating a hallmark style through consistency and dedication. That’s exactly the kind of “against all odds” boldness the #RIPMyFears concept transpired from. 🙏🏾❤️🏁

Just because someone carries it well, doesn’t mean it isn’t heavy. 🌏🤎 First quarter of 2023 has been nothing like I could’ve imagined, in the most polarizing crippling liberating relieving way. I have so much to express about Motherhood but first I’d like to take a second to celebrate this moment. 😭❤️ Cuauhtemóc, we’ve come a long way! You’ve worked hard, pushing through challenges that tested you and almost broke your spirit & will to continue. We are beyond proud that you stayed the course and are starting to enjoy the taste of your accomplishments. From someone who didn’t get the chance to go to prom, THIS is living your best life, and you know I’m living vicariously through you and your brothers! 🥹 I love you dearly, congratulations to you and all your class of 2023 !! 🎩🌹🎓✨

If there’s one thing about being a Mom, is that we’re never done learning and evolving. I can’t think of anything more ongoing or constant. To be a parent is learning how to be proactive and reactive at the same time. (If that makes any sense) Everything you think you know and could apply… every philosophy and strategy, will get challenged with every child you bring into the world. Each will each teach you and humble you differently. From day one, each will need you to be a slightly different version of yourself… and learning how to navigate that becomes the real journey. I’m incredibly grateful for my sons, and all they have enabled me to be, but also, I’m forever indebted to all the Mothers who came into my life at one point or another and the responsibility they felt to guide me. Before there was soft parenting, before any of us could turn to Google for all the answers… it really took a village of Mothers, Tias, Abuelitas, Madrinas, and Suegras to shape us and help us find our own way. Thankful for all that stuck with me and continues to serve me to this day, I would not be the Mother I am without them. ❤️🙏🏾 #InMyFeels #Motherhood

Contagious Culture Volume 3 is a group photography exhibition focused on the evolving underground of our post pandemic world. Based entirely on submissions, the show spotlights the work of professionals and amateurs alike. The prevailing ethic behind the show is a rejection of the dopamine-driven feedback loops on social media and a celebration of photography for art's sake. Through curated selections of graffiti, skateboarding, music, street photography, urban exploring, and low riding, the exhibiton creates a unique and collaborative presentation that acts like a yearbook of what's happening in a particular slice of culture today through the eyes of the photographers living it. 

Presented with special thanks to @hufworldwide and @californiacowboyscollective, as well as the 200+ photographers whose participation made this awesome exhibition and book possible.
